<methodology slug="kb-agents-md-context-pyramid">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>Three-tier context pyramid per directory: CLAUDE.md (@AGENTS.md hook), AGENTS.md (20-80 line brief for all agents), .agents/INDEX.md (on-demand catalogue). Enforced per source directory.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>agents-md</tag>
      <tag>context-management</tag>
      <tag>knowledge-base</tag>
      <tag>claude-code</tag>
      <tag>multi-agent</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>kb</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AGENTS.md Context Pyramid (CLAUDE.md → AGENTS.md → .agents/INDEX.md)</title>
    <summary>Organize every directory's agent context as a three-tier pyramid: `CLAUDE.md` is a one-line `@AGENTS.md` hook (the only thing Claude Code auto-loads), `AGENTS.md` is a 20-80 line essential brief auto-loaded via `@`-ref AND directly readable by non-Claude-Code agents (Agent SDK, Codex, aider, Cursor), and `.agents/INDEX.md` is the on-demand catalogue of deep references. The convention is enforced per directory — every source folder gets its own `CLAUDE.md` + `AGENTS.md` pair so agents entering at any depth get a calibrated brief without bulk-loading the whole tree.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Claude Code only auto-loads `CLAUDE.md`; standalone agents (Agent SDK, OpenAI Codex, GitHub Copilot Agent) only read `AGENTS.md`. Putting context in one breaks the other. The `CLAUDE.md = @AGENTS.md` hook is the single mechanic that lets one source of truth (`AGENTS.md`) serve both. The 20-80 line cap on `AGENTS.md` is empirical: above ~5k tokens the routing brief becomes its own context-pollution problem, and below 20 lines it cannot answer "what is this dir + how do I work in it". The per-directory pair ensures an agent that lands in `src/auth/` gets auth-specific context, not the repo-wide overview.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any repo where multiple agent kinds (Claude Code + Codex + aider + custom Agent SDK) need to share project context.</item>
        <item>Multi-package monorepos where each subpackage has different commands, gotchas, and dependencies.</item>
        <item>Long-lived projects where decision history and architecture deep-dives must stay searchable but not auto-loaded.</item>
        <item>Migrating from a single bloated `CLAUDE.md` to a routing-friendly layout.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-file scripts or one-off notebooks — the convention's overhead exceeds the benefit.</item>
        <item>Generated directories (build output, vendored deps) — they get rewritten and the docs would drift.</item>
        <item>Trivial leaf folders with under three files and no agent-relevant logic — keep the parent's `AGENTS.md` instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="three-tier-pyramid">
      <p>The pyramid separates auto-load (cheap, always paid) from on-demand (expensive, paid only when needed). CLAUDE.md is a one-line hook. AGENTS.md is the brief. .agents/INDEX.md is the catalogue of deep docs an agent loads only after deciding the dir is relevant.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For every directory containing source code or agent-relevant configuration, the repo MUST contain `CLAUDE.md` whose entire body is `@AGENTS.md` (one line, no other text), `AGENTS.md` between 20 and 80 lines (hard cap 120) covering what-this-dir-IS plus build/test/deploy commands plus active gotchas, and — when reference depth warrants — `.agents/INDEX.md` listing every deep-reference doc as a single Markdown table. CI MUST fail when any source directory is missing the `CLAUDE.md` + `AGENTS.md` pair or when `AGENTS.md` exceeds 120 lines.</statement>
        <rationale>Claude Code reads only `CLAUDE.md`; non-Claude-Code agents read only `AGENTS.md`. The `@AGENTS.md` hook routes one to the other so a single brief serves both. The 80-line target keeps auto-load context under ~5k tokens, the empirical break-even where the routing brief stops helping and starts crowding the working set.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
# CLAUDE.md (1 line)
@AGENTS.md

# AGENTS.md (40 lines)
# auth/

OAuth2 authorization-code flow with PKCE.
Runtime: Django 5, port 8000 (api), 8001 (api-dev).

## Commands
- Test: `uv run pytest auth/`
- Lint: `ruff check auth/`

## Gotchas
- `state` cookie is HttpOnly+SameSite=Lax; do NOT change.
- See `.agents/INDEX.md` for token-rotation deep dive.
        ]]></code>
        <note>Brief routes both Claude Code (via hook) and standalone agents (direct read) to the same authoritative context.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
# CLAUDE.md (200 lines)
# Auth module — full architecture
... (architecture diagram)
... (token rotation logic)
... (every gotcha ever)
        ]]></code>
        <note>Standalone agents never read this file. The auto-loaded context is now 200 lines of mostly-irrelevant material.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding extra prose, links, or directives to `CLAUDE.md` beyond the single `@AGENTS.md` line.</description>
        <reason>Drift between `CLAUDE.md` and `AGENTS.md` immediately desyncs Claude Code from every other agent; the hook stops being a hook and becomes a second source of truth that nobody updates.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/CLAUDE.md">The verbatim hook file.</reference>
      <reference path="templates/AGENTS.md">Skeleton brief with the six required sections.</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="per-directory-coverage">
      <p>An agent that opens a session with cwd in `src/auth/` should not need to climb the tree to find context. The pyramid is therefore replicated per directory with non-trivial logic; only empty or near-empty folders inherit from the parent.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>A directory MUST carry its own `CLAUDE.md` + `AGENTS.md` when ANY of these hold: it contains 3+ source files, it is a package boundary (own `pyproject.toml`/`package.json`/`go.mod`), it has commands or gotchas distinct from its parent, or it is referenced by another `AGENTS.md` as a navigation target. A directory MAY skip the pair only when it is an `__init__.py`-only folder, a generated/build output dir, a vendored dependency, or a leaf with under three files and zero distinct commands.</statement>
        <rationale>Per-directory coverage means an agent always reads exactly the brief that matches its working directory; without it, agents either auto-load the whole repo's context or guess. The skip rules prevent the convention from becoming busywork on trivial folders that would only repeat the parent.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
nero-core/
├── CLAUDE.md           # @AGENTS.md
├── AGENTS.md           # repo-wide brief
├── src/
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── CLAUDE.md   # @AGENTS.md
│   │   └── AGENTS.md   # auth-specific commands + gotchas
│   └── billing/
│       ├── CLAUDE.md
│       └── AGENTS.md
└── build/              # generated, no pair (skip rule)
        ]]></code>
        <note>Each package boundary has its own brief; the build folder is exempt as generated output.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
nero-core/
├── CLAUDE.md           # 600 lines covering every package
└── src/
    ├── auth/           # no pair, agents must climb
    └── billing/        # no pair, agents must climb
        ]]></code>
        <note>Single mega-brief at the root; agents working in `src/billing/` load 600 lines of mostly-auth context.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding `CLAUDE.md` + `AGENTS.md` to every leaf folder regardless of content (including empty `__init__.py`-only dirs).</description>
        <reason>Doubles maintenance cost without information gain; each pair must be touched on every refactor. The skip rules exist to keep the convention adoptable, not to be ignored.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/INDEX.md">Catalogue format for `.agents/INDEX.md`.</reference>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/CLAUDE.md" purpose="The one-line hook file every directory gets verbatim."/>
      <template path="templates/AGENTS.md" purpose="Skeleton with the six required sections (what-is, commands, state, key-paths, gotchas, links)."/>
      <template path="templates/INDEX.md" purpose=".agents/INDEX.md table format that lists deep-reference docs."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://agents.md/">agents.md — the cross-vendor AGENTS.md spec adopted by OpenAI Codex, Cursor, aider.</link>
      <link href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/memory">Claude Code memory docs — CLAUDE.md auto-load behaviour and @-import semantics.</link>
      <link href="https://github.com/openai/codex">OpenAI Codex — reads AGENTS.md per directory at session start.</link>
      <link href="https://docs.cursor.com/context/rules">Cursor Rules — also follow per-directory AGENTS.md discovery.</link>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
